        ],
        "documentHtml": "<section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;box-sizing:border-box;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255,252,245,0.99), rgba(255,248,235,0.96));border:1px solid rgba(146,64,14,0.16);box-shadow:0 12px 28px rgba(180,83,9,0.10);gap:14px;\"><div style=\"font:700 11px/1.2 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;letter-spacing:0.18em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#b45309;\">Title</div><div style=\"font:700 28px/1.12 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Graph Layout Authority</div><div style=\"height:1px;background:linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(245,158,11,0.45), rgba(245,158,11,0));\"></div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.65 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#4b5563;\">Disconnected is normal. Connection is explicit. Growth and layout decisions belong to the graph that owns the content.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Reality First</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Many graphs will never connect. Some graphs expose only narrow surfaces. The app can govern authored spaces, but not arbitrary web content. So the system must treat disconnection as normal and connection as explicit rather than assumed.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Local Authority First</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">A graph starts sovereign. It owns its own structure, what it exposes, and how its content grows. If a graph is not connected, nothing is wrong. Belonging is negotiated by references, views, summaries, and explicit expansion surfaces.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Connection Is Explicit</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Another graph can reference, summarize, expand into, or consume a surface only through what the source graph actually exposes. Connection is relational, not imperial.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Growth And Layout Belong To The Graph</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Growth and layout decisions should be made at the graph level. The host graph determines how content is added to its own space, what growth grammar is used by default, and when global relayout is allowed. The graph, not incidental cleanup, owns those decisions.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Relayout And Reroute Behavior</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Local growth owns normal editing. Manual placement is sticky. Global relayout is explicit and exceptional. Reroute is lighter than relayout. Preserve meaning over neatness.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Placement Provenance</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">The runtime should not infer layout authority forever from coordinates. It should record placement provenance. Nodes may be unplaced, auto-placed, manually-shaped, or part of a mixed graph. System-created, imported, expanded, and layout-generated positions should be marked auto-placed. User-dragged or intentionally arranged nodes should be marked manually-shaped. A graph with no meaningful placement may accept global relayout. A graph with manual placement should protect that meaning unless the user explicitly grants relayout authority.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Graph Shape First, Section Shapes Later</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Continue testing with layered growth as the default graph grammar. Later, graphs may allow local sections to choose a different internal shape, such as spiral or radial growth, without breaking the host graph’s larger boundary contract.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:22px 24px;border-radius:18px;background:linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(240,253,250,0.98), rgba(236,253,245,0.98));border:1px solid rgba(16,185,129,0.16);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#064e3b;\">Summary</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.75 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#065f46;\">A graph starts sovereign. Disconnected is normal. Connection is explicit. Layout and growth decisions belong to the graph that owns the content. Local growth is the default authority, manual placement is sticky, placement provenance should be recorded, and global relayout is explicit rather than ambient.</div></div></section>",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "document-view",
